---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Layout
  title="Dark Matter Context"
  description="The physics case for dark matter, axions, and why the DMRadio approach is well-motivated."
>

  <section class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow">Science Background</span>
      <h1>Dark Matter &amp; Axions</h1>
      <p class="desc">
        The evidence for dark matter is overwhelming. The question is: what is it made of?
        Axions and axion-like particles are among the best-motivated candidates, and DMRadio
        targets an unexplored corner of their parameter space.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Evidence for DM -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="two-col-60">
        <div>
          <span class="section-label">The Case for Dark Matter</span>
          <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">What Is Dark Matter?</h2>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            [Replace with an overview of the observational evidence for dark matter: galactic
            rotation curves (Rubin &amp; Ford), gravitational lensing (Bullet Cluster), large-scale
            structure formation, and the CMB power spectrum. ~2 paragraphs.]
          </p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            [Second paragraph: the standard WIMP paradigm has been extensively searched; null results
            from LHC and direct detection push theorists toward alternative candidates such as ultralight
            bosons.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Third paragraph: the cosmological abundance &mdash; dark matter makes up ~27% of the
            energy content of the Universe &mdash; motivates a broad search program spanning many decades
            of mass and coupling.]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1rem;">
          <div class="highlight-box">
            <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;color:var(--blue);">Dark Matter by the Numbers</h4>
            <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <tr><td style="padding:0.3rem 0;color:var(--gray-500);">DM fraction of universe</td><td style="font-weight:500;color:var(--gray-900);">~27%</td></tr>
              <tr><td style="padding:0.3rem 0;color:var(--gray-500);">Local DM density</td><td style="font-weight:500;color:var(--gray-900);">~0.3 GeV/cm&sup3;</td></tr>
              <tr><td style="padding:0.3rem 0;color:var(--gray-500);">Velocity dispersion</td><td style="font-weight:500;color:var(--gray-900);">~220 km/s</td></tr>
              <tr><td style="padding:0.3rem 0;color:var(--gray-500);">DM coherence time</td><td style="font-weight:500;color:var(--gray-900);">~10<sup>6</sup> / (m&middot;c&sup2;/&hbar;)</td></tr>
            </table>
          </div>
          <div class="diagram-placeholder" style="aspect-ratio:1;">
            <p><strong>Rotation curve figure</strong></p>
            <p>Replace with galaxy rotation curve plot</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Axions -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">The Axion</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Why Axions?</h2>
      <div class="two-col">
        <div>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">The Strong CP Problem</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
            [Explain the strong CP problem in QCD: why the theta parameter appears in the QCD
            Lagrangian, why it should produce an observable neutron electric dipole moment (nEDM),
            and why the experimentally measured value is &lt;10<sup>&minus;10</sup> rather than O(1).
            This fine-tuning problem is unnatural in the Standard Model.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Peccei-Quinn mechanism: introducing a new U(1) symmetry broken at scale f<sub>a</sub>
            dynamically drives &theta; to zero. The pseudo-Nambu-Goldstone boson of this breaking
            is the axion, with mass m<sub>a</sub> ~ &Lambda;<sup>2</sup><sub>QCD</sub>/f<sub>a</sub>.]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Cosmological Production</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
            [Describe the misalignment mechanism for axion dark matter production. If f<sub>a</sub>
            is large enough, the axion can account for the observed dark matter abundance. The
            corresponding mass range is [X&ndash;Y] &mu;eV, overlapping with DMRadio's target band.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [Also mention topological defect production (strings and domain walls) as an additional
            production mechanism, and how it extends the mass range where axions could be the
            dominant dark matter component.]
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Axion-photon coupling -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Detection Principle</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">Axion-Photon Coupling</h2>
      <div class="two-col-60">
        <div>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            [Explain the axion-photon coupling g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub>. The axion couples to
            two photons through the Lagrangian term &frac14; g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub> a F&tilde;F.
            In the presence of a strong external magnetic field B<sub>0</sub>, this interaction
            allows axions to resonantly convert to photons when the axion mass matches the photon
            frequency: m<sub>a</sub>c<sup>2</sup> = &hbar;&omega;.]
          </p>
          <p style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
            [Describe the expected signal power: P &prop; g<sup>2</sup><sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub>
            &rho;<sub>DM</sub> B<sup>2</sup><sub>0</sub> V Q / m<sub>a</sub>, where V is the effective
            volume and Q the quality factor. At DMRadio's target mass, this is an extraordinarily
            faint signal requiring quantum-limited detection.]
          </p>
          <p>
            [DFSZ and KSVZ benchmark models: these two canonical axion models predict specific values
            of g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub>. DMRadio aims to probe at or below these thresholds across
            its target mass range.]
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="diagram-placeholder">
            <p><strong>Exclusion plot</strong></p>
            <p>g<sub>a&gamma;&gamma;</sub> vs m<sub>a</sub></p>
            <p style="font-size:0.8rem;margin-top:0.5rem;">Replace with sensitivity projection figure</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- Landscape -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Experimental Landscape</span>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom:1.25rem;">DMRadio in Context</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom:2.5rem;max-width:680px;">
        Multiple experiments are pursuing axion dark matter across complementary mass ranges.
        DMRadio targets the sub-&mu;eV window not accessible to cavity-based haloscopes like ADMX.
      </p>
      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">DMRadio (this experiment)</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Lumped-element solenoidal resonator. Target: [X&ndash;Y] &mu;eV. Quantum-limited SQUID readout.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag tag-blue">Sub-&mu;eV</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">ADMX</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Microwave cavity haloscope at University of Washington. Currently covering 2&ndash;40 &mu;eV.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">&mu;eV range</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">HAYSTAC</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Yale/Berkeley/Colorado experiment. Higher-frequency cavity search with squeezed-state receiver.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">10&ndash;100 &mu;eV</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">ABRACADABRA</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">MIT solenoidal broadband search; demonstrated detection principle used by DMRadio.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">Sub-&mu;eV</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">CASPEr</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">NMR-based axion search via axion-nucleon coupling. Complementary to photon-coupling searches.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">Ultra-low mass</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;color:var(--blue);">SHAFT / AION</h4>
          <p style="font-size:0.875rem;">Atom interferometry-based searches for ultralight dark matter and gravitational waves.</p>
          <div style="margin-top:0.75rem;"><span class="tag">Ultra-light</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-sm" style="background:var(--gray-50);border-top:1px solid var(--gray-200);">
    <div class="container" style="text-align:center;">
      <h3 style="margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Ready to go deeper?</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;max-width:500px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;">
        Read our publications or explore how the experiment works in detail.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex;gap:1rem;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href={`${base}/experiment/`} class="btn btn-primary">The Experiment</a>
        <a href={`${base}/publications/`} class="btn btn-secondary">Publications</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
